external_knowledge:
- Significant impact on main species: refers to an average primary impact (P&D) greater than 50;
- 'Fishing techniques' refer to the methods used for fishing, such as trawling, longlining, etc.;
- The question also seeks to understand the relative impact on secondary species (L1) among those fishing techniques with a notable impact on primary species, ranked by their impact on secondary species from highest to lowest.

sql:
SELECT effort_reduction_percentage
FROM fishing_efforts
WHERE effort_reduction_percentage > 0;

SELECT AVG(effort_reduction_percentage) AS average_effort_reduction
FROM fishing_efforts
WHERE fishing_method = 'trawling';

external_knowledge:
"Significantly reduced" in the question corresponds to efforts where the reduction in fishing effort exceeds 20%; "major fishing attempts" refer to fishing efforts that have made a noticeable impact, defined by a reduction threshold; "zones" refer to marine areas.;
In marine conservation, an "open" status means fishing is allowed in the area; "total catch value" implies the economic worth of the catch associated with the fishing efforts.;
"More than five attempts" indicates a minimum threshold to ensure statistical significance in the fishing efforts data.

sql:
SELECT AVG(effort_reduction_percentage) AS average_effort_reduction
FROM fishing_efforts
WHERE fishing_location LIKE 'North%' AND average_pd_impact > 0.5;

SELECT AVG(f.effort_reduction_percentage) AS average_effort_reduction
FROM fishing_efforts f
INNER JOIN predictions p ON f.effort_id = p.effort_id;

SELECT AVG(percentage_area_unfished) AS average_unfished_area
FROM fishing_efforts
WHERE fishing_method = 'Longlining';
